<li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130114221614/http://history1800s.about.com/od/abrahamlincoln/a/lincolncooperu.htm">"Lincoln's Cooper Union Address Propelled Him to the White House. A Speaking Engagement in New York City Makes an Illinois Lawyer a Political Star"</a>. About.com (A part of The New York Times Company). Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://history1800s.about.com/od/abrahamlincoln/a/lincolncooperu.htm">the original</a> on January 14, 2013<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">February 24,</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Lincoln%27s+Cooper+Union+Address+Propelled+Him+to+the+White+House.+A+Speaking+Engagement+in+New+York+City+Makes+an+Illinois+Lawyer+a+Political+Star&amp;rft.pub=About.com+%28A+part+of+The+New+York+Times+Company%29&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fhistory1800s.about.com%2Fod%2Fabrahamlincoln%2Fa%2Flincolncooperu.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACooper+Union+speech" class="Z3988"></span></span>
